NYU Shanghai January Term for Study Away Students | NYU Shanghai                                            Jump to navigation                                      Search form      Search                         中文               Research   Campus Life   Academic Life   Admissions   About                                       Main menu        About NYU Shanghai   Admissions & Financial Aid   Academic Life   Campus Life   Research             Gateways        Prospective Students   Current Students   Faculty   Employees   Community   News   Events / Calendar                         You are here Home > NYU Shanghai January Term for Study Away Students            NYU Shanghai January Term for Study Away Students                                                  NYU Shanghai offers three January Term (J-Term) courses in Shanghai in January 2015, all of which are open to study away students from New York. These courses give students the opportunity to study away in Shanghai and experience the excitement and wonder of Shanghai, one of the most dynamic cities in Asia. Students benefit from NYU’s facilities, professors, and full-time academic and student life staff. Site visits to historic sites and neighborhoods arranged by NYU enable students to explore this city beyond the campus. Before you apply, we encourage you to learn more about NYU Shanghai .   NYU Shanghai January Term 2015 courses are currently NOT available to visiting (non-NYU) students.       Program Dates   January 4 - January 23, 2015   Arrivals/Check-in: January 4, 2015 (Students will be able to check in starting Sunday, January 4, 2015 at 8am. The NYU Shanghai campus is located 35-40 minutes by taxi from the Pudong International Airport (PVG). Students will find public transportation or taxi's readily available, information about arrivals will be sent closer to the program start date. )   Orientation: January 5, 2015   Classes begin: January 5, 2015   Classes end: January 22, 2015   Check-out/departure: January 23, 2015       Location   Shanghai       Academics   All students may take one course during the three-week January term. The following three NYU Shanghai courses will be offered in Shanghai this J-Term 2015. All these courses are instructed in English.       1. Creativity & Innovation BUSH-SHU 10 J    4 credits   To compete today in a fast-changing world, organizations and individuals need a steady stream of innovative strategies and unexpected solutions to stay ahead of the game—solutions that revive stagnant markets or completely reinvent the competitive dynamics of an industry. This course is about fostering a culture of creative thinking that provides the framework and motivation to generate those strategies and execute those solutions. It is an essential skill for any student with the desire to transform organizational processes and behaviors, and a willingness to challenge the status quo.The course provides many opportunities to apply these new ways of thinking through class exercises and a course project, where you will develop innovative solutions for a chosen topic.       2. Neighborhood, Map, Phone INTM-SHU 10J   4 credits   In this class, students will work in small groups to explore and annotate the neighborhood around NYU's Shanghai campus. Students will learn how to use basic digital mapping and annotation tools, on both phones and computers, to understand and document the neighborhood.   The first week will introduce simple tools for layering images and text onto existing maps. The second week will include two exercises -- the creation of a scavenger hunt for the rest of the class, and a structured "neighborhood walk" for others to use. The third week will be class discussion of the current state of user-created maps, with attention to future social and economic uses of these tools. The class will culminate with a presentation of these possible futures by each small group.       3. What can Neuroscience Tell us about Free Will? NEUR-SHU 10J   4 credits   The concept of free will plays a central role in society, in particular in the criminal justice system. In this course, we will explore the concept of free will and related topics in neuroscience such as intention and self-control. We will cover the evidence from neuroscience that argues that behavior is, under normal conditions, not deterministic, thus providing a material basis for the concept of individual agency.  We will then address the neuroscience evidence for cases where individual agency is reduced through external influence via learning and the reward and punishment systems. Finally, we will examine the most extreme cases of this, psychiatric disorders that reduce agency: addiction, compulsive disorders, and anxiety disorders.       Credit   Academic credit for the NYU Shanghai J-Term programs is treated like any other credit awarded for coursework at NYU. The NYU Shanghai J-Term courses will be recorded on the student’s NYU transcript, and the final grades from such courses will be calculated into a student’s NYU grade point average (GPA). It is your responsibility to work with your home school academic advisor and major department to determine whether and how a course might count towards your degree requirements.       Level   Undergraduate.        Eligibility   Enrollment is only open to undergraduates from NYU New York. Students' university records will be reviewed. Students with a 3.0 grade point average or higher are encouraged to apply.       Application   NYU New York Students will find a link to the study away application in their student center in Albert. An academic committee will review the application and select the students for the 3 courses. The application deadline for J-term 2015 courses is Saturday, November 15, 2014 . Students will be informed as to whether they have been accepted by Monday, November 24, 2014 .       Registration   Once accepted, students should consult their home school advisor to determine how their course will be transferred back to their NYU degree. If accepted, students will be enrolled manually by the NYU Shanghai Registrar’s Office.       Costs   4 points. Each student may enroll in one 4 credit class.   Tuition = $5,156   Activity Fee = $300   Housing Fee = $1,000 (Students will be staying in double rooms at a local 4 star hotel behind the NYU Shanghai campus)   Books = All the books and course materials will be available to you upon arrival in Shanghai. The book and course material fees will be charged based on the requirement of the specific course.   Required Insurance = All students will be enrolled in the HTH worldwide insurance program. The insurance rate for the students travelling for the J Term would be the HTH Study Abroad Rate of $11.34 per week or $34.02 for the three weeks.   *Students are responsible for purchasing round trip airfare, meals and personal expenses. There are required costs beyond what they have to pay to NYU. Financial aid may be available from students' home school, but not from NYU Shanghai.       Pre-Departure Preparation/Visa: NYU Shanghai will provide you with the necessary documents to process a student study visa. It is important to check with the Office of Global Services or utilize the Global Check Plus application found in NYUhome to check if you have a specific visa requirements, it may vary for individuals and based on your nationality. If you have general questions or need help, please email shanghai.student-mobility@nyu.edu for further information.       Activities: During your time in Shanghai the Office of Student Life will be arranging local activities to provide you with an intensive and in depth interaction with the city of Shanghai.       Contact Info   Please contact shanghai.advising@nyu.edu with any questions.                                                     About NYU Shanghai Vision and Mission Statement   Leadership   Statement of Labor Values   Technology Services   Work Here   Getting Around Campus   FAQs   Contact Us     Admissions & Financial Aid Chinese Admissions   Chinese Financial Support   US/International Admissions   US/International Financial Aid   Financial Aid FAQs   Contact Us   Welcome Center     Academic Life Academic Calendar   Our Curriculum   Our Majors   Our Faculty   Our Library   Study Away   Academic Support   Registration Services   Non-Degree Educational Programs     Campus Life New Student Programs   Office of the Dean of Students   Athletics and Recreation   Career Development   Getting Settled   Health and Wellness   Residential Life and Housing   Student Involvement   Student Services   Be Safe     Research Research Resources   Research News   Research at NYU Shanghai               Gateways      Prospective Students   Current Students   Faculty   Employees   Community   News   Events / Calendar                        NYU SHANGHAI   Copyright © 2015 NYU Shanghai. NYU Shanghai January Term for Study Away Students | NYU Shanghai                                            Jump to navigation                                      Search form      Search                         中文               Research   Campus Life   Academic Life   Admissions   About                                       Main menu        About NYU Shanghai   Admissions & Financial Aid   Academic Life   Campus Life   Research             Gateways        Prospective Students   Current Students   Faculty   Employees   Community   News   Events / Calendar                         You are here Home > NYU Shanghai January Term for Study Away Students            NYU Shanghai January Term for Study Away Students                                                  NYU Shanghai offers three January Term (J-Term) courses in Shanghai in January 2015, all of which are open to study away students from New York. These courses give students the opportunity to study away in Shanghai and experience the excitement and wonder of Shanghai, one of the most dynamic cities in Asia. Students benefit from NYU’s facilities, professors, and full-time academic and student life staff. Site visits to historic sites and neighborhoods arranged by NYU enable students to explore this city beyond the campus. Before you apply, we encourage you to learn more about NYU Shanghai .   NYU Shanghai January Term 2015 courses are currently NOT available to visiting (non-NYU) students.       Program Dates   January 4 - January 23, 2015   Arrivals/Check-in: January 4, 2015 (Students will be able to check in starting Sunday, January 4, 2015 at 8am. The NYU Shanghai campus is located 35-40 minutes by taxi from the Pudong International Airport (PVG). Students will find public transportation or taxi's readily available, information about arrivals will be sent closer to the program start date. )   Orientation: January 5, 2015   Classes begin: January 5, 2015   Classes end: January 22, 2015   Check-out/departure: January 23, 2015       Location   Shanghai       Academics   All students may take one course during the three-week January term. The following three NYU Shanghai courses will be offered in Shanghai this J-Term 2015. All these courses are instructed in English.       1. Creativity & Innovation BUSH-SHU 10 J    4 credits   To compete today in a fast-changing world, organizations and individuals need a steady stream of innovative strategies and unexpected solutions to stay ahead of the game—solutions that revive stagnant markets or completely reinvent the competitive dynamics of an industry. This course is about fostering a culture of creative thinking that provides the framework and motivation to generate those strategies and execute those solutions. It is an essential skill for any student with the desire to transform organizational processes and behaviors, and a willingness to challenge the status quo.The course provides many opportunities to apply these new ways of thinking through class exercises and a course project, where you will develop innovative solutions for a chosen topic.       2. Neighborhood, Map, Phone INTM-SHU 10J   4 credits   In this class, students will work in small groups to explore and annotate the neighborhood around NYU's Shanghai campus. Students will learn how to use basic digital mapping and annotation tools, on both phones and computers, to understand and document the neighborhood.   The first week will introduce simple tools for layering images and text onto existing maps. The second week will include two exercises -- the creation of a scavenger hunt for the rest of the class, and a structured "neighborhood walk" for others to use. The third week will be class discussion of the current state of user-created maps, with attention to future social and economic uses of these tools. The class will culminate with a presentation of these possible futures by each small group.       3. What can Neuroscience Tell us about Free Will? NEUR-SHU 10J   4 credits   The concept of free will plays a central role in society, in particular in the criminal justice system. In this course, we will explore the concept of free will and related topics in neuroscience such as intention and self-control. We will cover the evidence from neuroscience that argues that behavior is, under normal conditions, not deterministic, thus providing a material basis for the concept of individual agency.  We will then address the neuroscience evidence for cases where individual agency is reduced through external influence via learning and the reward and punishment systems. Finally, we will examine the most extreme cases of this, psychiatric disorders that reduce agency: addiction, compulsive disorders, and anxiety disorders.       Credit   Academic credit for the NYU Shanghai J-Term programs is treated like any other credit awarded for coursework at NYU. The NYU Shanghai J-Term courses will be recorded on the student’s NYU transcript, and the final grades from such courses will be calculated into a student’s NYU grade point average (GPA). It is your responsibility to work with your home school academic advisor and major department to determine whether and how a course might count towards your degree requirements.       Level   Undergraduate.        Eligibility   Enrollment is only open to undergraduates from NYU New York. Students' university records will be reviewed. Students with a 3.0 grade point average or higher are encouraged to apply.       Application   NYU New York Students will find a link to the study away application in their student center in Albert. An academic committee will review the application and select the students for the 3 courses. The application deadline for J-term 2015 courses is Saturday, November 15, 2014 . Students will be informed as to whether they have been accepted by Monday, November 24, 2014 .       Registration   Once accepted, students should consult their home school advisor to determine how their course will be transferred back to their NYU degree. If accepted, students will be enrolled manually by the NYU Shanghai Registrar’s Office.       Costs   4 points. Each student may enroll in one 4 credit class.   Tuition = $5,156   Activity Fee = $300   Housing Fee = $1,000 (Students will be staying in double rooms at a local 4 star hotel behind the NYU Shanghai campus)   Books = All the books and course materials will be available to you upon arrival in Shanghai. The book and course material fees will be charged based on the requirement of the specific course.   Required Insurance = All students will be enrolled in the HTH worldwide insurance program. The insurance rate for the students travelling for the J Term would be the HTH Study Abroad Rate of $11.34 per week or $34.02 for the three weeks.   *Students are responsible for purchasing round trip airfare, meals and personal expenses. There are required costs beyond what they have to pay to NYU. Financial aid may be available from students' home school, but not from NYU Shanghai.       Pre-Departure Preparation/Visa: NYU Shanghai will provide you with the necessary documents to process a student study visa. It is important to check with the Office of Global Services or utilize the Global Check Plus application found in NYUhome to check if you have a specific visa requirements, it may vary for individuals and based on your nationality. If you have general questions or need help, please email shanghai.student-mobility@nyu.edu for further information.       Activities: During your time in Shanghai the Office of Student Life will be arranging local activities to provide you with an intensive and in depth interaction with the city of Shanghai.       Contact Info   Please contact shanghai.advising@nyu.edu with any questions.                                                     About NYU Shanghai Vision and Mission Statement   Leadership   Statement of Labor Values   Technology Services   Work Here   Getting Around Campus   FAQs   Contact Us     Admissions & Financial Aid Chinese Admissions   Chinese Financial Support   US/International Admissions   US/International Financial Aid   Financial Aid FAQs   Contact Us   Welcome Center     Academic Life Academic Calendar   Our Curriculum   Our Majors   Our Faculty   Our Library   Study Away   Academic Support   Registration Services   Non-Degree Educational Programs     Campus Life New Student Programs   Office of the Dean of Students   Athletics and Recreation   Career Development   Getting Settled   Health and Wellness   Residential Life and Housing   Student Involvement   Student Services   Be Safe     Research Research Resources   Research News   Research at NYU Shanghai               Gateways      Prospective Students   Current Students   Faculty   Employees   Community   News   Events / Calendar                        NYU SHANGHAI   Copyright © 2015 NYU Shanghai. If so, taking a single course during the January term might be your best option! All NYU Shanghai students may take one course during the three-week January term in 2015. J term 2015 courses run from January 5 to 23, 2015.   There are three different options of J term courses available now for NYU Shanghai students:     Shanghai courses in Shanghai       Abu Dhabi courses in Shanghai and around the global network        New York courses.      1. Shanghai Courses   The following three NYU Shanghai courses will be offered in Shanghai this J Term 2015:   (1). Creativity & Innovation BUSH-SHU 10 J (will count as a non-Finance elective or general elective)   (2). Neighborhood, Map, Phone INTM-SHU 10J (will count as Science, Technology and Society OR Skills Development course for IMA major , or general elective)   (3). What can Neuroscience Tell us about Free Will? NEUR-SHU 10J (will count as Science, Technology and Society or general elective)   You can look up the course descriptions in Albert. Course registration will be available on Monday, October 20, 2014 . Second year students will have an earlier registration time than first-year students.   2. Abu Dhabi Courses   NYU Abu Dhabi offers courses in sites throughout the global network during J term. The available courses are posted on this website . Students must apply and be accepted into an Abu Dhabi course. The application can be found here . The deadline to apply is October 15, 2014. The tuition and fee information for Abu Dhabi J term courses can be found here . There is no financial aid available. If you're accepted, Abu Dhabi will inform you about the registration process.   3. New York Courses    Students may review the J term course offerings in New York by going to Albert. Course registration opens on October 20, 2014 (Eastern Standard Time). There is NO application process for NYU Shanghai students to apply for J term courses offered in New York.
